reveals that these private entrepreneurs regarded the California citrus industry as their primary model of emulation. Utilizing an innovative multidisciplinary approach, Nahum Karlinsky vividly reconstructs the social fabric, economic structure, and ideological tenets of the Jewish citrus industry of Palestine in the early twentieth century. Also accentuated is the role of Palestinian-Arab citrus growers, whose industry predated that of their Jewish counterparts, and the complex relationship between the two national sectors that operated side by side.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aCitrus fruit industryzPalestinexHistory. 0aEntrepreneurshipzPalestinexHistory. 0aFruit tradezPalestinexHistory. 4aArea Studies : Israel Studies. 4aArea Studies : Middle East Studies. 4aBusiness and Economics : Agricultural Economics. 4aHistory : History. 4aJewish Studies : Jewish Studies. 7aTechnology & Engineering / Agriculture / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791482919423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791482919/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles